# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-liberation-front
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The program began in 1968 as a bi-weekly television show hosted by Mike Wallace and Harry Reasoner.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The two sat on opposite sides of the cream-colored set, though the set's color was later changed to black, the color still in use.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The show used a large stopwatch during transition periods and highlighted its topics through chroma key—both techniques are still used.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In 1972, the program began airing from 6:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Eastern time, although this time was sometimes disrupted by broadcasting of NFL games on Sundays.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Since then, the show has generally kept the Sunday evening format, although the start time has occasionally been shifted.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The program generally starts at 7:00 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] If sports programming is airing that afternoon, *60 Minutes* starts at 7:30 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The show is hosted by correspondents who do not share screen time with each other.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Full-time hosts include Lesley Stahl and Bill Whitaker.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Several spinoffs have been made, including international formats of the show.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Starting in 2006, the background color was changed to red, the title text color changed to white, and the stopwatch was shifted to the upright position.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The program employed a magazine format similar to that of the Canadian program *W5*, which had premiered two years earlier.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] It pioneered many of the most important investigative journalism procedures and techniques, including re-editing interviews, hidden cameras, and "gotcha journalism" visits to the home or office of an investigative subject.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Similar programs sprang up in Australia and Canada during the 1970s, as well as on local television news.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Initially, *60 Minutes* aired as a bi-weekly show hosted by Mike Wallace and Harry Reasoner debuting on September 24, 1968, and alternating weeks with other CBS News productions on Tuesday evenings at 10:00 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] A meditation by Wallace and Reasoner on the relation between perception and reality.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Wallace said that the show aimed to "reflect reality".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The first "magazine-cover" chroma key was a photo of two helmeted policemen (for the Clark interview segment).
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Wallace and Reasoner sat in chairs on opposite sides of the set, which had a cream-colored backdrop; the more famous black backdrop (which is still used as of 2020) did not appear until the following year.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The logo was in Helvetica type with the word "Minutes" spelled in all lower-case letters; the logo most associated with the show (rendered in Eurostile type with "Minutes" spelled in uppercase) did not appear until about 1974.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Further, to extend the magazine motif, the producers added a "Vol. xx, No. xx" to the title display on the chroma key; modeled after the volume and issue number identifications featured in print magazines, this was used until about 1971.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The trademark stopwatch, however, did not appear on the inaugural broadcast; it would not debut until several episodes later.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Alpo dog food was the sole sponsor of the first program.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Don Hewitt, who had been a producer of the *CBS Evening News* with Walter Cronkite, sought out Wallace as a stylistic contrast to Reasoner.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] According to one historian of the show, the idea of the format was to make the hosts the reporters, to always feature stories that were of national importance but focused upon individuals involved with, or in conflict with, those issues, and to limit the reports' airtime to around 13 minutes.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] However, the initial season was troubled by lack of network confidence, as the program did not garner ratings much higher than that of other CBS News documentaries.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* struggled under that stigma during its first three years.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Changes to *60 Minutes* came fairly early in the program's history.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] When Reasoner left CBS to co-anchor ABC's evening newscast (he would return to CBS and *60 Minutes* in 1978), Morley Safer joined the team in 1970, and he took over Reasoner's duties of reporting less aggressive stories.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] By 1971, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) introduced the Prime Time Access Rule, which freed local network affiliates in the top 50 markets (in practice, the entire network) to take a half-hour of prime time from the networks on Mondays through Saturdays and one full hour on Sundays.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] After a six-month hiatus in late 1971, CBS found a prime place for *60 Minutes* in a portion of that displaced time, 6:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Central Time) on Sundays in January 1972.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] This proved somewhat less than satisfactory, however, because in order to accommodate CBS telecasts of late afternoon National Football League (NFL) games, *60 Minutes* went on hiatus during the fall from 1972 to 1975 (and the summer of 1972).
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] This took place because football telecasts were protected contractually from interruptions in the wake of the infamous "Heidi Bowl" incident on NBC in November 1968.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Eventually, during the summers of 1973 through 1975, CBS did allow the program back onto the prime time schedule proper, on Fridays in 1973 and Sundays the two years thereafter, as a replacement for programs aired during the regular television season.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] It was only when the FCC returned an hour to the networks on Sundays (for news or family programming), which had been taken away from them four years earlier, in a 1975 amendment to the Access Rule, that CBS finally found a viable permanent timeslot for *60 Minutes*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] When the family-oriented drama *Three for the Road* ended after a 12-week run in the fall, the news magazine took its place at 7:00 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] This move, and the addition of then-White House correspondent Dan Rather to the reporting team, made the program into a strong ratings hit and, eventually, a general cultural phenomenon.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] This was no less than a stunning reversal of the historically poor ratings performances of documentary programs on network television.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] By 1976, *60 Minutes* became the top-rated program on Sunday nights in the US.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] By 1979, it had achieved the #1 spot among all television programs in the Nielsen ratings, unheard of before for a news broadcast in prime time.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] This success translated into great profits for CBS; advertising rates increased from $17,000 per 30-second spot in 1975 to $175,000 in 1982.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The program sometimes does not start until after 7:00 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Eastern, due largely to CBS Sports live sporting events.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] At the conclusion of an NFL game, *60 Minutes* will air in its entirety and delay all subsequent programs.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] However, in the Pacific time zone, *60 Minutes* is always able to start at its scheduled time as live sports coverage ends earlier in the afternoon.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Starting in the 2012–2013 season, in order to accommodate a new NFL scheduling policy that the second game of a doubleheader start at 4:25 p.m., CBS changed the scheduled start time of *60 Minutes* to 7:30 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Eastern time (or game conclusion) for Eastern and Central Time Zone stations which are receiving a game in that window.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Eastern/Pacific (or game conclusion if a late single game is airing in the eastern markets) on stations which are not broadcasting a late game in a given week (or for Western time zones even if a doubleheader airs).
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Since the 2023–2024 season, the show began to have occasional 90-minute episodes.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] For most of the 1970s, the program included *Point/Counterpoint*, in which a liberal and conservative commentator debated an issue.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] This segment originally featured James J.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Kilpatrick representing the conservative side and Nicholas von Hoffman for the liberal, with Shana Alexander taking over for von Hoffman after he departed in 1974.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The segment was an innovation that caught the public imagination as live versions of competing editorials.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In 1979, Alexander asked Hewitt to raise the $350 per week pay; Hewitt declined, and the segment ended.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] A similar concept was revived briefly in March 2003 featuring Bob Dole and Bill Clinton, former opponents in the 1996 presidential election.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The pair agreed to do ten segments (titled *Clinton/Dole* and *Dole/Clinton* in alternating weeks), but these did not continue into the 2003–2004 fall season.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Reports indicated that the segments were considered too gentlemanly, in the style of the earlier *Point/Counterpoint*, and lacked the feistiness of *Crossfire*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] From 1978 to 2011, the program usually ended with (usually light-hearted and humorous) commentary by Andy Rooney expounding on topics of wildly varying importance, ranging from international politics, to economics, and his personal philosophy on everyday life.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] One recurring topic was measuring the amount of coffee in coffee cans.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Rooney's pieces, particularly one in which he referred to actor Mel Gibson as a "wacko", on occasion led to complaints from viewers.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] After four weeks without Rooney, *60 Minutes* lost 20% of its audience.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] CBS management concluded that it was in their best interest to have Rooney return immediately.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Rooney published several books documenting his contributions to the program, including *Years of Minutes* and *A Few Minutes with Andy Rooney*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Rooney retired from *60 Minutes*, delivering his final commentary on October 2, 2011; it was his 1,097th commentary over his 34-year career on the program.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] He died one month later on November 4, 2011.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On November 13, 2011, *60 Minutes* featured an hour-long tribute to Rooney and his career and included a rebroadcast of his final commentary segment.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The opening sequence features a *60 Minutes* "magazine cover" with the show's trademark, an Aristo stopwatch, intercut with preview clips of the episode's stories.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The sequence ends with each of the correspondents and hosts introducing themselves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The last host who appears then says, "Those stories tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] When Rooney was a prominent fixture, the final line was "Those stories and Andy Rooney, tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Before that, and whenever Rooney did not appear, the final line was "Those stories and more, tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The stopwatch counts off each of the broadcast's 60 minutes, starting from zero at the beginning of each show.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] It is seen during the opening title sequence, before each commercial break, and at the tail-end of the closing credits, and each time it appears it displays (within reasonable accuracy) the elapsed time of the episode to that point.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On October 29, 2006, the opening sequence changed from a black background, which had been used for over a decade, to white.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Also, the gray background for the Aristo stopwatch in the "cover" changed to red, the color for the title text changed to white, and the stopwatch itself changed from the diagonal position it had been oriented in for 31 years to an upright position.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Videos and transcripts of *60 Minutes* editions, as well as clips that were not included in the broadcast are available on the program's website.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In September 2010, the program launched a website called "60 Minutes Overtime", in which stories broadcast on-air are discussed in further detail.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Previously the show had a partnership with Yahoo! for distribution of extra content.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Based on viewership ratings, *60 Minutes* is the most successful program in American television history since it was moved into its present timeslot in 1975.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* was a top ten show for 23 seasons in a row (1977–2000), an unsurpassed record, and has made the Top 20 for every season since the 1976–1977 season, except from 2005 to 2008.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On November 16, 2008, the edition featuring an interview with President-elect Barack Obama, earned a total viewership of 25.1 million viewers.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On October 6, 2013, the broadcast (which was delayed by 44 minutes that evening due to a Denver Broncos–Dallas Cowboys NFL game) drew 17.94 million viewers; retaining 63% of the 28.32 million viewers of its lead-in, and making it the most watched *60 Minutes* broadcast since December 16, 2012.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On December 1, 2013, the broadcast (delayed 50 minutes due to a Broncos–Kansas City Chiefs game) was watched by 18.09 million viewers, retaining 66% of its NFL lead-in (which earned 28.11 million viewers during the 7:00 p.m. hour).
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On March 25, 2018, the edition featuring Stormy Daniels giving details on her alleged affair with President Donald Trump drew 22.1 million viewers, the most since the 2008 Obama interview.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The broadcast was delayed due to the NCAA men's basketball regional final on CBS between Kansas and Duke going to overtime.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] As of June 26, 2017, *60 Minutes* had won a total of 138 Emmy Awards, a record for American primetime programs.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The show received an Investigative Reporter and Editor medal for their segment "The Osprey", documenting a Marine cover-up of deadly flaws in the V-22 Osprey aircraft.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In 1983, a report by Morley Safer, "Lenell Geter's in Jail", helped exonerate a Texas man who was wrongly convicted and imprisoned for armed robbery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] As of 2021, *60 Minutes* is the longest continuously running program of any genre scheduled during American network prime time.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Eastern Time on Sundays since December 7, 1975 (although since 2012, it moves to 7:30 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Eastern Time on Sundays if CBS has a late NFL game).
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The show has been praised for landmark journalism and received many awards.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On November 23, 1986, *60 Minutes* aired a segment greenlit by Hewitt, concerning the Audi 5000 automobile, a popular German luxury car.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The story covered a supposed problem of "unintended acceleration" when the brake pedal was pushed, with emotional interviews with six people who sued Audi (unsuccessfully) after they crashed their cars, including one woman whose six-year-old son had been killed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In the *60 Minutes* segment footage was shown of an Audi 5000 with the accelerator "moving down on its own", accelerating the car.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] It later emerged that an expert witness employed by one of the plaintiffs modified the accelerator with a concealed device, causing the "unintended acceleration".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Independent investigators concluded that this "unintended acceleration" was most likely due to driver error, where the driver let their foot slip off the brake and onto the accelerator.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Tests by Audi and independent journalists showed that even with the throttle wide open, the car would simply stall if the brakes were actually being used.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The incident devastated Audi sales in the United States, which did not rebound for 15 years.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The initial incidents which prompted the report were found by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and Transport Canada to have been attributable to operator error, where car owners had depressed the accelerator pedal instead of the brake pedal.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] CBS issued a partial retraction, without acknowledging the test results of involved government agencies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Years later, *Dateline NBC*, a rival to *60 Minutes*, was found guilty of similar tactics regarding the fuel tank integrity of General Motors pickup trucks.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] A segment aired in December, 1980, concerning the alleged Jeep CJ-5 *high rollover risk* as demonstrated in Insurance Institute for Highway Safety testing.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The demonstration was a Jeep rolling over during an extreme turn at 20 mph (32 km/h), something that would not cause other cars to roll over.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] It was deemed by *60 Minutes* reporters as the "most dangerous thing on four wheels".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] After the show aired, many people were concerned about the safety of the vehicle, and following sales plummeted.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] This tarnished the reputation of the Jeep CJ; the model was discontinued in 1986.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Years after the incident occurred, it was found that the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety had attempted to roll the car 435 times, only having 8 rollovers.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The show had also failed to mention/show that there were weights hanging on spots of the vehicle that had caused the vehicle to have a higher rollover risk.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In February 1989, *60 Minutes* aired a report by the Natural Resources Defense Council claiming that the use of daminozide (Alar) on apples presented an unacceptably high health risk to consumers.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Apple sales dropped and CBS was sued unsuccessfully by apple growers.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Alar was subsequently banned for use on food crops in the U.S. by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On March 3, 1991, *60 Minutes* broadcast "Werner Erhard," which dealt with controversies involving Erhard's personal and business life.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] A year after the *60 Minutes* piece aired, Erhard filed a lawsuit against CBS, claiming that the broadcast contained several "false, misleading and defamatory" statements about him.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] One month after filing the lawsuit, Erhard filed for dismissal.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Erhard later told Larry King in an interview that he dropped the suit after receiving legal advice telling him that in order to win it, he had to prove not only that CBS knew the allegations were false but also that CBS acted with malice.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In 1995, former Brown & Williamson Vice President for Research and Development Jeffrey Wigand provided information to *60 Minutes* producer Lowell Bergman pertaining to B&W having systematically hidden the health risks of their cigarettes .
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Furthermore, it was alleged that B&W had introduced foreign agents (such as fiberglass and ammonia) with the intent of enhancing the effect of nicotine.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Bergman began to produce a piece based upon the information, but ran into opposition from Don Hewitt who, along with CBS lawyers, feared a billion-dollar lawsuit from Brown and Williamson for tortious interference for encouraging Wigand to violate his non-disclosure agreement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] A number of people at CBS would benefit from a sale of CBS to Westinghouse Electric Corporation, including the head of CBS lawyers and CBS News.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Also, because of the interview, the son of CBS President Laurence Tisch (who also controlled Lorillard Tobacco) was among the people from the big tobacco companies at risk of being caught having committed perjury.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Due to Hewitt's hesitation, *The Wall Street Journal* instead broke Wigand's story.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The *60 Minutes* piece was eventually aired with substantially altered content and minus some of the most damning evidence against B&W.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The exposé of the incident was published in an article in *Vanity Fair* by Marie Brenner, entitled "The Man Who Knew Too Much".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In 1997, *60 Minutes* alleged that agents of the U.S.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Customs Service ignored drug trafficking across the Mexico–United States border at San Diego.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The only evidence was a memorandum apparently written by Rudy Camacho, who was the head of the San Diego branch office.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Based on this memo, CBS alleged that Camacho had allowed trucks belonging to a particular firm to cross the border unimpeded.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Mike Horner, a former Customs Service employee, had passed the memos on to *60 Minutes*, and even provided a copy with an official stamp.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Camacho was not consulted about the piece, and his career was devastated in the immediate term as his own department placed suspicion on him.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In the end, it turned out that Horner had forged the documents as an act of revenge for his treatment within the Customs Service.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Camacho sued CBS and settled for an undisclosed amount of money in damages.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* founder Don Hewitt was forced to issue an on-air retraction.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] A legal battle between archaeologists and the Umatilla tribe over the remains of a skeleton, nicknamed Kennewick Man, was reported by *60 Minutes* on October 25, 1998, to which the Umatilla tribe reacted negatively.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The tribe considered the segment heavily biased in favor of the scientists, cutting out important arguments, such as explanations of the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The report focused heavily on the racial politics of the controversy and also added inflammatory arguments, such as questioning the legitimacy of Native American sovereignty—much of the racial focus of the segment was later reported to have been either unfounded and/or misinterpreted.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On March 12, 2000, *60 Minutes* aired an interview with Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] At the time, McVeigh had already been convicted and sentenced to death for the bombing of the Alfred P.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Murrah Federal Building in April 1995, and the subsequent deaths of 168 people.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On the program, McVeigh was given the opportunity to vent against the government.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Following the program, a federal policy called the Special Confinement Unit Media Policy was enacted prohibiting face-to-face interviews with death row inmates.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] A federal inmate challenged the policy in *Hammer v.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit upheld the prison policy.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In March 2010, the United States Supreme Court declined to hear an appeal in the case, and the policy limiting media access to death row inmates remains in place.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] CBS refuses to show the entire interview, and has stated no reasons.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The Killian documents controversy involved six documents critical of George W.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Bush's service in the Texas Air National Guard from 1972-73.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Four of these documents were presented as authentic in a *60 Minutes II* episode aired on September 8, 2004, less than two months before the 2004 presidential election, but it was later found that CBS had failed to authenticate the documents.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Subsequently, several typewriter and typography experts concluded the documents are forgeries, as have some media sources.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] No forensic document examiners or typography experts authenticated the documents, which may not be possible without original documents.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Bill Burkett, claimed to have burned the originals after faxing copies to CBS.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The incident was dramatized for the feature-length film, *Truth*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On March 29, 2009, a segment titled "The Internet Is Infected" aired on *60 Minutes*, which featured an interview with Don Jackson, a data protection professional for SecureWorks.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Jackson himself declared in the program that "a part of [his] job is to know the enemy".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] However, during the interview, Jackson showed a photo of Finnish upper-level comprehensive school pupils and misidentified them as Russian hackers.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In the photo, one of the children wears a jacket with the coat of arms of Finland on it.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Another one wears a cap which clearly has the logo of Karjala, a Finnish brand of beer, on it.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The principal of the school in Taivalkoski confirmed that the photo was taken at the school about five years before the program was broadcast.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The photo's exact origins are unknown, but it is widely known in Finland, having been originally posted to the Finnish social networking site IRC-Galleria in the early 2000s.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] It spread all over Finnish internet communities, and even originated a couple of patriotically titled (but intentionally misspelled) mock sites.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* later issued a correction and on-air apology.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] He also claimed to have visited a Benghazi hospital earlier that night where he saw Ambassador Christopher Stevens' body.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In the days following the report, Davies' personal actions were challenged.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The FBI, which had interviewed Davies several times and considered him a credible source, said the account Davies had given them was different from what he told *60 Minutes*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Davies stood by his story, but the inconsistency ultimately prompted *60 Minutes* to conclude it was a mistake to include Davies in their report.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] After the correction, a journalistic review was conducted by Al Ortiz, CBS News' executive director of standards and practices.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Ortiz determined that red flags about Davies' account were missed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Davies had told the program and written in his book that he told an alternative version of his actions to his employer, who he said had demanded that he stay inside his Benghazi villa as the attack unfolded.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] That alternative version was shared with U.S. authorities; *60 Minutes* was unable to prove the story Davies had told them was true.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Davies' book, *The Embassy House*, was published two days after the *60 Minutes* report, by Threshold Editions, part of the Simon and Schuster unit of CBS.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] It was pulled from shelves once *60 Minutes* issued its correction.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On November 26, 2013, Logan was forced to take a leave of absence due to the errors in the Benghazi report.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On December 15, 2013, *60 Minutes* aired a report on the workings of the National Security Agency (NSA) that was widely criticized as misleading and a biased "puff piece".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Complaints included that the Agency's perspective was presented unchallenged and that privacy campaigners were not invited to present the counter-arguments to the Agency's claims.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] These claims included NSA denials of "potentially extralegal" data collection.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The story was reported by John Miller, who once worked in the office of the Director of National Intelligence.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On March 30, 2014, *60 Minutes* presented a story on the Tesla Model S luxury electric automobile, with Scott Pelley conducting an interview with CEO Elon Musk concerning the car brand as well as his company SpaceX.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Within a day, the automotive blog site Jalopnik reported that the sounds accompanying footage of the car shown during the story were actually sounds from a traditional gasoline engine dubbed over the footage, when in reality the electric car makes no such sounds.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] CBS released a statement explaining that the sound was the result of an audio editing error, and subsequently removed the sound from the online version of the piece.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] However, several news outlets, as well as Jalopnik itself, expressed doubt over the authenticity of this explanation, noting the similar scandal involving Tesla Motors and the *New York Times* in 2013.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] After the resignation of CBS news head Les Moonves, an investigation into sexual harassment at CBS, including *60 Minutes*, uncovered evidence of long-running sexual harassment issues stemming from behavior of producers Jeff Fager and Don Hewitt.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Subsequently, Palm Beach County Mayor Dave Kerner accused *60 Minutes* of reporting "intentionally false" information, while Karol Markowicz of the *New York Post* characterized Alfonsi as coming off as a "political activist" in the segment.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] A spokesperson for *60 Minutes* defended the story for having included DeSantis' response to the accusation.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] PolitiFact stated that by omitting DeSantis' remarks on why the state partnered with Publix to distribute vaccines, the clip could be considered to be "deceptive editing".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On May 16, 2021, Anderson Cooper's story in *60 Minutes* on the flaws in facial recognition technology used by the police resulting in incorrect identification of people of color received backlash for denying credit to the black female researchers who pioneered the field.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The segment was criticized by the Algorithmic Justice League for "deliberately excluding the groundbreaking and award-winning work of prominent black women AI researchers Joy Buolamwini, Dr.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Timnit Gebru, and Inioluwa Deborah Raji".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The segment was called out for its hypocrisy for failing to credit black women for their pioneering work in a segment highlighting how facial recognition software often leaves out black, Asian, and female faces.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] CBS later issued a statement explaining that these researchers were not included due to time restrictions of the segment.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On December 7, 2024, Donald Trump filed a $20 billion lawsuit against CBS and its parent company, Paramount Global, alleging that the network deceptively edited an interview with Vice President Kamala Harris on *60 Minutes* to sway public opinion in her favor.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] The lawsuit, submitted in the lead-up to the 2024 presidential election, claims that the editing distorted Harris's response regarding Middle East policy.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Both parties agreed to enter mediation, coinciding with a planned $8 billion merger between Paramount and Skydance, which requires approval from the Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Within Paramount, there was reportedly internal disagreement over whether to settle the dispute, as the producers of *60 Minutes* maintained their conduct was appropriate and opposed offering an apology.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In early April 2025, Trump expressed his "hope" that the FCC would punish CBS for running on *60 Minutes* stories on Ukraine and Greenland that he disapproved of.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Trump filed a lawsuit in Texas accusing CBS of violating the state's Deceptive Trade Practices Act, a consumer protection law.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On April 22, 2025, Bill Owens resigned as the show's executive producer, telling staff he believed he no longer had journalistic independence.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] He said in a memo that the show would continue to cover the second Trump administration the same way it has covered others.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] In the "Last Minute" segment of the show on April 27, 2025, Scott Pelley praised Owens for ensuring that the types of controversial stories the show had covered since its creation, most recently the Gaza war and the Trump administration, were covered fairly.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On May 19, 2025, CBS News chief executive Wendy McMahon followed Bill Owens in resigning.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] McMahon explained in a memo to staff, “The past few months have been challenging.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On July 2, 2025, Paramount agreed to a $16 million settlement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] As part of the deal, the company did not apologize or admit wrongdoing, agreed to release full transcripts of interviews with future U.S. presidential candidates after they air, and stated that the funds will go to Trump's future presidential library.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On the July 14, 2025, episode of CBS's late-night talk show *The Late Show with Stephen Colbert*, host Stephen Colbert called the settlement a "big fat bribe".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Three days later, CBS announced that it would not renew Colbert's contract with the network, and that it would end the *Late Show* franchise at the conclusion of the 2025–26 television season.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Although CBS claimed that the decision to end the show was "purely" financial, it was suspected that the decision may have been politically-motivated due to Colbert's comments and regular history of satirizing the Trump administration.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On December 21, 2025, CBS News abruptly pulled a planned segment on El Salvador's Terrorism Confinement Center (CECOT) and President Trump's deportation of Venezuelan migrants from that night's episode, and announced that it would be postponed to a future date.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Correspondent Sharyn Alfonsi accused Bari Weiss—who had recently been named editor-in-chief of CBS News—of intervening for political reasons, despite the segment having been cleared by the network's staff.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On December 22, Canadian broadcaster Global accidentally made the original cut of the episode containing the CECOT story available on its video on demand platform, causing it to be widely disseminated online.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Alfonsi stated in a email memorandum to colleagues that the production team did request comments and interviews from White House officials, the State Department, and the Department of Homeland Security, which were all refused.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] On January 18, 2026, the segment aired alongside a piece on the relations between Minneapolis citizens and ICE officers after the death of Renée Good.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] Correspondent Scott Pelley was fired in June 2026.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p01] He complained about management, including CBS News Chief Bari Weiss, and the incoming executive-producer of the show, Nick Bilton.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The main *60 Minutes* show has created a number of spin-offs over the years.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In September 2004, the program was marred by controversy when it aired a report alleging that presidential candidate George W.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] Bush had previously been suspended from the Texas Air National Guard as unfit for duty; the claims were found to have been based on falsified documents received by the show's staff.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The show later moved to Friday nights in July 2005 (rebranding back to *60 Minutes II*), and aired its final episode on September 2, 2005.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In 2011, CNBC began airing a *60 Minutes* spin-off of its own, called *60 Minutes on CNBC*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] Hosted by Lesley Stahl and Steve Kroft, it aired updated business-related reports seen on the original broadcasts and offers footage that was not included when the segments first aired.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In 2013, CBS's sister premium television network Showtime premiered *60 Minutes Sports*, a monthly spin-off focused on sports-related stories and classic interviews from the show's archives.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] Personalities from CBS Sports also contributed to the program; correspondents included Sharyn Alfonsi and Armen Keteyian.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The spin-off was considered a competitor to HBO's *Real Sports*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In June 2020, the show launched *60 in 6* on Quibi, featuring original weekly 6-minute programs.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] Correspondents were Enrique Acevedo, Seth Doane, Wesley Lowery, and Laurie Segall.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] It was originally set to launch in April 2020.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] On the June 21, 2020, broadcast of *60 in 6*, Doane covered the show's exposure to COVID-19 in a piece titled "CBS News Battles COVID-19".
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The piece revealed that CBS News had flown in staffers, including from Seattle and Rome, in early March 2020 to begin filming promotional material for *60 in 6*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] This brought COVID-19-positive people in close contact with CBS employees; as a result, CBS Broadcast Center and several other buildings in Manhattan were temporarily closed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] Quibi went bankrupt in December 2020 and the program concluded with it.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In March 2021, Paramount+ premiered *60 Minutes+*, a weekly spin-off aimed at a younger audience.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The correspondents from *60 in 6* returned for this spin-off, as well as producer Jonathan Blakely.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In January 2022, the show was cancelled after 30 episodes.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] For the *60 Minutes* 25th anniversary program in 1993, Charles Kuralt revisited notable stories and celebrity appearances and also interviewed Don Hewitt and correspondents, both the active and some former ones.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The Australian version of *60 Minutes* premiered on February 11, 1979.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] It still airs each Sunday night at 7:30 p.m. on the Nine Network and affiliates.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] Although Nine Network has the rights to the format, as of 2007, it does not have rights to stories from the American program, which is owned by competitor 10 News Australia after Network Ten's acquisition by CBS in 2017.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] Nevertheless, stories from the flagship *60 Minutes* program in the U.S. often air on the Australian program by subleasing them from Ten.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In 1981, *60 Minutes* won a Logie Award for their investigation of lethal abuses at the Chelmsford psychiatric hospital in Sydney.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In the mid-1980s, an edited version (approx.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] This version retained the English-language track of the original but also featured German dubbing.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The New Zealand version of *60 Minutes* has aired on national television since 1989, when it was originally launched on TV3.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In 1992, the rights were acquired by TVNZ, who began broadcasting it in 1993.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The network aired the program for nine years before dropping it in 2002 for its own program, entitled *Sunday*, which is currently the highest-rated current affairs show broadcast on New Zealand television, followed by *20/20*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] *60 Minutes* was broadcast by rival network TV3, before switching to the Sky Television owned Prime channel in 2013, when the contract changed hands.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] In 1992, the GNT channel brought its original version with dubbed subtitles from that country.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] And later, in 2004, Rede Bandeirantes, planned a licensed localized version, but the plan was cancelled.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] And even so that year, it returned as a frame, i.e. a rubric in the program *Domingo Espetacular* on Rede Record, a competitor of Rede Globo's program *Fantástico*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] SIC Notícias acquired the broadcasting rights to the program in 2001.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The original episodes were shown in Portugal with introductory and final comments by journalist Mário Crespo, who conducted the program until 2014.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] It is presently hosted by anchors of the aforementioned network on a rotational basis, who eventually adopted the previous model.
[src:animal-liberation-front/60-minutes-p02] The news program of National Broadcasting of Chile (TVN), the public television network in that country, was named *60 Minutos* ("60 Minutes") from 1975 to 1988, but the program had no association with the American version and no investigative reporting.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-liberation-front/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The first country to fully outlaw slavery was France in 1315, though it was later used in its colonies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The first country to abolish and punish slavery for indigenous people was Spain with the New Laws in 1542.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Under the actions of Toyotomi Hideyoshi, chattel slavery was abolished across Japan since 1590, though other forms of forced labor were used during World War II.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The first and only country to self-liberate from slavery was a former French colony, Haiti, as a result of the Revolution of 1791–1804.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The British abolitionist movement began in the late 18th century, and the 1772 Somersett case established that slavery did not exist in English law.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1807, the slave trade was made illegal throughout the British Empire, though existing slaves in British colonies were not liberated until the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In the United States, Pennsylvania and Vermont were the first states to abolish slavery, Vermont in 1777 and Pennsylvania in 1780 (Vermont did not join the Union until 1791).
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] By 1804, the rest of the northern states had abolished slavery, but it remained legal in southern states.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] By 1808, the United States outlawed the importation of slaves and in 1865 outlawed slavery except as a punishment.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In Eastern Europe, groups organized to abolish the enslavement of the Roma in Wallachia and Moldavia between 1843 and 1855, and to emancipate the serfs in Russia in 1861.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The United States would pass the 13th Amendment in December 1865 after having just fought a bloody Civil War, ending slavery "except as a punishment for crime".
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1888, Brazil became the last country in the Americas to outlaw slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] As the Empire of Japan annexed Asian countries, from the late 19th century onwards, archaic institutions including slavery were abolished in those countries.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1948, slavery was declared illegal in the United Nations' Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] By this time, the Arab world was the only region in the world where institutional chattel slavery was still legal.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Slavery in Saudi Arabia, slavery in Yemen and slavery in Dubai were abolished in 1962–1963, with slavery in Oman following in 1970.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Mauritania is the latest country to officially abolish slavery, with a presidential decree in 1981.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Today, child and adult slavery and forced labor are illegal in almost all countries, as well as being against international law, but human trafficking for labor and for sexual slavery continues to affect tens of millions of adults and children.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Balthild of Chelles, herself a former slave, queen consort of Neustria and Burgundy by marriage to Clovis II, became regent in 657 since the king, her son Chlothar III, was only five years old.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] At some unknown date during her rule, she abolished the trade of slaves, although not slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Moreover, her (and contemporaneous Saint Eligius') favorite charity was to buy and free slaves, especially children.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Slavery started to dwindle and would be superseded by serfdom.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1315, Louis X, king of France, published a decree proclaiming that "France signifies freedom" and that any slave setting foot on French soil should be freed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] This prompted subsequent governments to circumscribe slavery in the overseas colonies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Some cases of African slaves freed by setting foot on French soil were recorded such as the example of a Norman slave merchant who tried to sell slaves in Bordeaux in 1571.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] He was arrested and his slaves were freed according to a declaration of the Parlement of Guyenne which stated that slavery was intolerable in France, although it is a misconception that there were 'no slaves in France'; thousands of African slaves were present in France during the 18th century.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Born into slavery in Saint Domingue, Thomas-Alexandre Dumas became free when his father brought him to France in 1776.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] As in other New World colonies, the French relied on the Atlantic slave trade for labor for their sugar cane plantations in their Caribbean colonies; the French West Indies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In addition, French colonists in *Louisiane* in North America held slaves, particularly in the South around New Orleans, where they established sugarcane plantations.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Louis XIV's *Code Noir* regulated the slave trade and institution in the colonies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] It included the right to marry, gather publicly or take Sundays off.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Although the *Code Noir* authorized and codified cruel corporal punishment against slaves under certain conditions, it forbade slave owners to torture them or to separate families.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] It also demanded enslaved Africans receive instruction in the Catholic faith, implying that Africans were human beings endowed with a soul, a fact French law did not admit until then.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] It resulted in a far higher percentage of Black people being free in 1830 (13.2% in Louisiana compared to 0.8% in Mississippi).
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] They were on average exceptionally literate, with a significant number of them owning businesses, properties, and even slaves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Other free people of colour, such as Julien Raimond, spoke out against slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The *Code Noir* also forbade interracial marriages, but it was often ignored in French colonial society and the mulattoes became an intermediate caste between whites and blacks, while in the British colonies mulattoes and blacks were considered equal and discriminated against equally.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] During the Age of Enlightenment, many philosophers wrote pamphlets against slavery and its moral and economical justifications, including Montesquieu in *The Spirit of the Laws* (1748) and Denis Diderot in the *Encyclopédie*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, Jacques Pierre Brissot founded the Society of the Friends of the Blacks (*Société des Amis des Noirs*) to work for the abolition of slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] After the Revolution, on 4 April 1792, France granted free people of colour full citizenship.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The slave revolt, in the largest Caribbean French colony of Saint-Domingue in 1791, was the beginning of what became the Haitian Revolution led by formerly enslaved people like Georges Biassou, Toussaint L'Ouverture, and Jean-Jacques Dessalines.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion swept through the north of the colony, and with it came freedom to thousands of enslaved blacks, but also violence and death.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1793, French Civil Commissioners in St.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Domingue and abolitionists, Léger-Félicité Sonthonax and Étienne Polverel, issued the first emancipation proclamation of the modern world (Decree of 16 Pluviôse An II).
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The Convention sent them to safeguard the allegiance of the population to revolutionary France.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The proclamation resulted in crucial military strategy as it gradually brought most of the black troops into the French fold and kept the colony under the French flag for most of the conflict.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The connection with France lasted until blacks and free people of colour formed L'armée indigène in 1802 to resist Napoleon's Expédition de Saint-Domingue.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Victory over the French in the decisive Battle of Vertières finally led to independence and the creation of present Haiti in 1804.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The convention, the first elected Assembly of the First Republic (1792–1804), on 4 February 1794, under the leadership of Maximilien Robespierre, abolished slavery in law in France and its colonies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Abbé Grégoire and the Society of the Friends of the Blacks were part of the abolitionist movement, which had laid important groundwork in building anti-slavery sentiment in the metropole.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The first article of the law stated that "Slavery was abolished" in the French colonies, while the second article stated that "slave-owners would be indemnified" with financial compensation for the value of their slaves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The French constitution passed in 1795 included in the declaration of the Rights of Man that slavery was abolished.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] During the French Revolutionary Wars, French slave-owners joined the counter-revolution en masse and, through the Whitehall Accord, they threatened to move the French Caribbean colonies to British control, as Great Britain still allowed slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Fearing secession from these islands, successfully lobbied by planters and concerned about revenues from the West Indies, and influenced by the slaveholder family of his wife, Napoleon Bonaparte decided to re-establish slavery after becoming First Consul.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] He promulgated the law of 20 May 1802 and sent military governors and troops to the colonies to impose it.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] On 10 May 1802, Colonel Delgrès launched a rebellion in Guadeloupe against Napoleon's representative, General Richepanse.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The rebellion was repressed, and slavery was re-established.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The news of the Law of 4 February 1794 that abolished slavery in France and its colonies and the revolution led by Colonel Delgrès sparked another wave of rebellion in Saint-Domingue.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] From 1802 Napoleon sent more than 20,000 troops to the island, two-thirds died, mostly from yellow fever.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Seeing the failure of the Saint-Domingue expedition, in 1803 Napoleon decided to sell the Louisiana Territory to the United States.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The French governments initially refused to recognize Haïti.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] It forced the nation to pay a substantial amount of reparations (which it could ill afford) for losses during the revolution and did not recognize its government until 1825.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] France was a signatory to the first multilateral treaty for the suppression of the slave trade, the Treaty for the Suppression of the African Slave Trade (1841), but the king, Louis Philippe I, declined to ratify it.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] On 27 April 1848, under the Second Republic (1848–1852), the decree-law written by Victor Schœlcher abolished slavery in the remaining colonies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The state bought the slaves from the *colons* (white colonists; *Békés* in Creole), and then freed them.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] At about the same time, France started colonizing Africa and had gained possession of much of West Africa by 1900.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1905, the French abolished slavery in most of French West Africa.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The French also attempted to abolish Tuareg slavery following the Kaocen Revolt.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In the region of the Sahel, slavery has long persisted.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The abolition wasn't strictly put in place.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Several french territories kept practising slavery until 1904 as was the case in Senegal or 1894 in Soudan.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The abolition was not strictly enforced.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Passed on 10 May 2001, the Taubira law officially acknowledges slavery and the Atlantic slave trade as a crime against humanity.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] 10 May was chosen as the day dedicated to recognition of the crime of slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] James Oglethorpe was among the first to articulate the Enlightenment case against slavery, banning it in the Province of Georgia on humanitarian grounds, and arguing against it in Parliament.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Soon after Oglethorpe's death in 1785, Sharp and More united with William Wilberforce and others in forming the Clapham Sect.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The Somersett case in 1772, in which a fugitive slave was freed with the judgement that slavery did not exist under English common law, helped launch the British movement to abolish slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Though anti-slavery sentiments were widespread by the late 18th century, many colonies and emerging nations continued to use slave labor: Dutch, French, British, Spanish, and Portuguese territories in the West Indies, South America, and the Southern United States.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] After the American Revolution established the United States, many Loyalists who fled the Northern United States immigrated to the British province of Quebec, bringing an English majority population as well as many slaves, leading the province to ban the institution in 1793 (see Slavery in Canada).
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1787, the Society for Effecting the Abolition of the Slave Trade was formed in London.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The last known form of enforced servitude of adults (villeinage) had disappeared in England by the beginning of the 17th century.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1569 a court considered the case of Cartwright, who had bought a slave from Russia.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The court ruled English law could not recognize slavery, as it was never established officially.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] This ruling was overshadowed by later developments; it was upheld in 1700 by the Lord Chief Justice John Holt when he ruled that a slave became free as soon as he arrived in England.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] During the English Civil Wars of the mid-seventeenth century, sectarian radicals challenged slavery and other threats to personal freedom.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Their ideas influenced many antislavery thinkers in the eighteenth century.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In addition to English colonists importing slaves to the North American colonies, by the 18th century, traders began to import slaves from Africa, India and East Asia (where they were trading) to London and Edinburgh to work as personal servants.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Men who migrated to the North American colonies often took their East Indian slaves or servants with them, as East Indians have been documented in colonial records.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Some of the first freedom suits, court cases in the British Isles to challenge the legality of slavery, took place in Scotland in 1755 and 1769.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Each of the slaves had been baptized in Scotland and challenged the legality of slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] They set the precedent of legal procedure in British courts that would later lead to successful outcomes for the plaintiffs.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In these cases, deaths of the plaintiff and defendant, respectively, brought an end before court decisions.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] African slaves were not bought or sold in London but were brought by masters from other areas.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Together with people from other nations, especially non-Christian, Africans were considered foreigners, not able to be English subjects.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] At the time, England had no naturalization procedure.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The African slaves' legal status was unclear until 1772 and Somersett's Case, when the fugitive slave James Somersett forced a decision by the courts.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Somersett had escaped, and his master, Charles Steuart, had him captured and imprisoned on board a ship, intending to ship him to Jamaica to be resold into slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] While in London, Somersett had been baptized; three godparents issued a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] As a result, Lord Mansfield, Chief Justice of the Court of the King's Bench, had to judge whether Somersett's abduction was lawful or not under English common law.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] No legislation had ever been passed to establish slavery in England.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The case received national attention, and five advocates supported the action on behalf of Somersett.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Although the exact legal implications of the judgement are unclear when analysed by lawyers, the judgement was generally taken at the time to have determined that slavery did not exist under English common law and was thus prohibited in England.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The decision did not apply to the British overseas territories; by then, for example, the American colonies had established slavery by positive laws.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Somersett's case became a significant part of the common law of slavery in the English-speaking world and it helped launch the movement to abolish slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] After reading about Somersett's Case, Joseph Knight, an enslaved African who had been purchased by his master John Wedderburn in Jamaica and brought to Scotland, left him.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Married and with a child, he filed a freedom suit, on the grounds that he could not be held as a slave in Great Britain.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Wedderburn* (1778), Wedderburn said that Knight owed him "perpetual servitude".
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The Court of Session of Scotland ruled against him, saying that chattel slavery was not recognized under the law of Scotland, and slaves could seek court protection to leave a master or avoid being forcibly removed from Scotland to be returned to slavery in the colonies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] But at the same time, legally mandated, hereditary slavery of Scots persons in Scotland had existed from 1606 and continued until 1799, when colliers and salters were emancipated by an act of the Parliament of Great Britain (39 Geo.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Skilled workers, they were restricted to a place and could be sold with the works.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] 28) was intended to end what the act referred to as "a state of slavery and bondage", but that was ineffective, necessitating the 1799 act.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In the 1776 book *The Wealth of Nations*, Adam Smith argued for the abolition of slavery on economic grounds.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Smith pointed out that slavery incurred security, housing, and food costs that the use of free labor would not, and opined that free workers would be more productive because they would have personal economic incentives to work harder.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The death rate (and thus repurchase cost) of slaves was also high, and people are less productive when not allowed to choose the type of work they prefer, are illiterate, and are forced to live and work in miserable and unhealthy conditions.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The free labor markets and international free trade that Smith preferred would also result in different prices and allocations that Smith believed would be more efficient and productive for consumers.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Prior to the American Revolution, there were few significant initiatives in the American colonies that led to the abolitionist movement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Kent was the lawyer who took on most of the cases of slaves suing their masters for personal illegal enslavement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] He was the first lawyer to successfully establish a slave's freedom.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In addition, Brigadier General Samuel Birch created the *Book of Negroes*, to establish which slaves were free after the war.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1783, an anti-slavery movement began among the British public to end slavery throughout the British Empire.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] After the formation of the Committee for the Abolition of the Slave Trade in 1787, William Wilberforce led the cause of abolition through the parliamentary campaign.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson became the group's most prominent researcher, gathering vast amounts of data on the trade.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] One aspect of abolitionism during this period was the effective use of images such as the famous Josiah Wedgwood "Am I Not A Man and a Brother?" anti-slavery medallion of 1787.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Clarkson described the medallion as "promoting the cause of justice, humanity and freedom".
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The 1792 Slave Trade Bill passed the House of Commons mangled and mutilated by the modifications and amendments of Pitt, it lay for years, in the House of Lords.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Biographer William Hague considers the unfinished abolition of the slave trade to be Pitt's greatest failure.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 was passed by the British Parliament on 25 March 1807, making the slave trade illegal throughout the British Empire.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Britain used its influence to coerce other countries to agree to treaties to end their slave trade and allow the Royal Navy to seize their slave ships.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Britain enforced the abolition of the trade because the act made trading slaves within British territories illegal.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] However, the act repealed the Amelioration Act 1798 which attempted to improve conditions for slaves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The end of the slave trade did not end slavery as a whole.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In the 1820s, the abolitionist movement revived to campaign against the institution of slavery itself.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1823 the first Anti-Slavery Society, the Society for the Mitigation and Gradual Abolition of Slavery Throughout the British Dominions, was founded.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Many of its members had previously campaigned against the slave trade.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] On 28 August 1833, the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 was passed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] It purchased the slaves from their masters and paved the way for the abolition of slavery throughout the British Empire by 1838, after which the first Anti-Slavery Society was wound up.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1839, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society was formed by Joseph Sturge, which attempted to outlaw slavery worldwide and also to pressure the government to help enforce the suppression of the slave trade by declaring slave traders to be pirates.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The world's oldest international human rights organization, it continues today as Anti-Slavery International.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Thomas Clarkson was the key speaker at the World Anti-Slavery Convention it held in London in 1840.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In the principalities of Wallachia and Moldavia, the government held slavery of the Roma (often referred to as Gypsies) as legal at the beginning of the 19th century.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The progressive pro-European and anti-Ottoman movement, which gradually gained power in the two principalities, also worked to abolish that slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Between 1843 and 1855, the principalities emancipated all of the 250,000 enslaved Roma people.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Bartolomé de las Casas was a 16th-century Spanish Dominican priest, the first resident Bishop of Chiapas (Central America, today Mexico).
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] As a settler in the New World he witnessed and opposed the poor treatment and virtual slavery of the Native Americans by the Spanish colonists, under the encomienda system.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] He advocated before King Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor on behalf of rights for the natives.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Las Casas for 20 years worked to get African slaves imported to replace natives; African slavery was everywhere and no one talked of ridding the New World of it, though France had abolished slavery in France itself and there was talk in other countries about doing the same.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] However, Las Casas had a late change of heart, and became an advocate for the Africans in the colonies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] His book, *A Short Account of the Destruction of the Indies*, contributed to Spanish passage of colonial legislation known as the New Laws of 1542, which abolished native slavery for the first time in European colonial history.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] It ultimately led to the Valladolid debate, the first European debate about the rights of colonized people.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] During the early 19th century, slavery expanded rapidly in Brazil, Cuba, and the United States, while at the same time the new republics of mainland Spanish America became committed to the gradual abolition of slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] During the Spanish American wars for independence (1810–1826), slavery was abolished in most of Latin America, though it continued until 1873 in Puerto Rico, 1886 in Cuba, and 1888 in Brazil (where it was abolished by the *Lei Áurea*, the "Golden Law").
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Chile declared freedom of wombs in 1811, followed by the United Provinces of the River Plate in 1813, Colombia and Venezuela in 1821, but without abolishing slavery completely.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] While Chile abolished slavery in 1823, Argentina did so with the signing of the Argentine Constitution of 1853.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Slavery was abolished in Uruguay during the *Guerra Grande*, by both the government of Fructuoso Rivera and the government in exile of Manuel Oribe.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Throughout the growth of slavery in the American South, Nova Scotia became a destination for black refugees leaving Southern Colonies and United States.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] While many blacks who arrived in Nova Scotia during the American Revolution were free, others were not.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Black slaves also arrived in Nova Scotia as the property of White American Loyalists.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1772, prior to the American Revolution, Britain determined that slavery could not exist in the British Isles followed by the *Knight v.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Wedderburn* decision in Scotland in 1778.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] This decision, in turn, influenced the colony of Nova Scotia.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1788, abolitionist James Drummond MacGregor from Pictou published the first anti-slavery literature in Canada and began purchasing slaves' freedom and chastising his colleagues in the Presbyterian church who owned slaves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Led by Richard John Uniacke, in 1787, 1789 and again on 11 January 1808, the Nova Scotian legislature refused to legalize slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Two chief justices, Thomas Andrew Lumisden Strange (1790–1796) and Sampson Salter Blowers (1797–1832) were instrumental in freeing slaves from their owners in Nova Scotia.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] They were held in high regard in the colony.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] By the end of the War of 1812 and the arrival of the Black Refugees, there were few slaves left in Nova Scotia.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The Slave Trade Act 1807 outlawed the slave trade in the British Empire and the Slavery Abolition Act 1833 outlawed slavery altogether.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] With slaves escaping to New York and New England, legislation for gradual emancipation was passed in Upper Canada (1793) and Lower Canada (1803).
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In Upper Canada, the Act Against Slavery of 1793 was passed by the Assembly under the auspices of John Graves Simcoe.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] It was the first legislation against slavery in the British Empire.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Under its provisions no new slaves could be imported, slaves already in the province would remain enslaved until death, and children born to female slaves would be slaves but must be freed at the age of 25.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The last slaves in Canada gained their freedom when slavery was abolished in the entire British Empire by the Slavery Abolition Act 1833.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In his book *The Struggle For Equality*, historian James M.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] McPherson defines an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional, and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] He does not include antislavery activists such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party, which called for the gradual ending of slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Benjamin Franklin, a slaveholder for much of his life, became a leading member of the Pennsylvania Society for the Abolition of Slavery, the first recognized organization for abolitionists in the United States.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, Northern states abolished slavery, beginning with the 1777 Constitution of Vermont, followed by Pennsylvania's gradual emancipation act in 1780.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Other states with more of an economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, also passed gradual emancipation laws, and by 1804, all the Northern states had abolished it, although this did not mean that already enslaved people were freed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Some had to work without wages as "indentured servants" for two more decades, although they could no longer be sold.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The 1836–1837 campaign to end free speech in Alton, Illinois, culminated in the 7 November 1837 mob murder of abolitionist newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy, which was covered in newspapers nationwide, causing a rise in membership in abolitionist societies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] By 1840 more than 15,000 people were members of abolitionist societies in the United States.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In the 1850s in the fifteen states constituting the American South, slavery was legally established.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] While it was fading away in the cities as well as in the border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cotton for export, or sugar, tobacco, or hemp.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] According to the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] American abolitionism was based in the North, although there were anti-abolitionist riots in several cities.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In the South abolitionism was illegal, and abolitionist publications, like The Liberator, could not be sent to Southern post offices.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Amos Dresser, a white alumnus of Lane Theological Seminary, was publicly whipped in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing abolitionist publications.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In addition, laws were passed to further repress slaves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] These laws included anti-literacy laws and anti-gathering laws.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The anti-gathering laws were applied to religious gatherings of free blacks and slaves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] These laws, passed around the 1820–1850 period, were blamed in the South on Northern abolitionists.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] As one slaveowner wrote, "I can tell you.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Abolitionism in the United States became a popular expression of moralism, operating in tandem with other social reform efforts, such as the temperance movement, and much more problematically, the women's suffrage movement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison (founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society) and writers Wendell Phillips, John Greenleaf Whittier, and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners of using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The Republican Party wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because it believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] White Southern leaders said that the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the territories made them second-class citizens and, as the *Dred Scott* decision held, infringed slaveholders' property rights.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and the labor of enslaved people decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the Confederacy's firing on Fort Sumter, a Union fort in South Carolina.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] When Lincoln called for troops to suppress the rebellion, four more slave states seceded.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, four slave states, known as the border states (Maryland, Missouri, Delaware, and Kentucky), chose to remain in the Union.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] On 16 April 1862, Abraham Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, abolishing slavery in Washington D.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of escaped slaves from the South rushing to Union lines.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, called contrabands, so that they would not be returned to their masters in the Confederacy.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] On 1 January 1863, Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which was an executive order of the U.S. government that changed the legal status of 3 million slaves in the Confederacy from "slave" to "henceforward ... free".
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Though slaves were legally freed by the Proclamation, they became actually free by escaping to federal lines, or by advances of federal troops.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Even before the Emancipation Proclamation, many former slaves served the federal army as teamsters, cooks, laundresses, and laborers, as well as scouts, spies, and guides.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Plantation owners sometimes moved the Black people they claimed to own as far as possible out of reach of the Union army.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] By "Juneteenth" (19 June 1865, in Texas), the Union Army controlled all of the Confederacy and liberated all its slaves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The owners were never compensated; nor were freed slaves compensated by former owners.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The border states were exempt from the Emancipation Proclamation, but they too (except Delaware) began their own emancipation programs.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] As the war dragged on, both the federal government and Union states continued to take measures against slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In June 1864, the Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, which required free states to aid in returning escaped slaves to slave states, was repealed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The state of Maryland abolished slavery on 13 October 1864.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Missouri abolished slavery on 11 January 1865.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] West Virginia, which had been admitted to the Union in 1863 as a slave state, but on the condition of gradual emancipation, fully abolished slavery on 3 February 1865.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Constitution took effect in December 1865, seven months after the end of the war, and finally ended slavery for non-criminals throughout the United States.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] It also abolished slavery among the Indian tribes, including the Alaska tribes that became part of the U.S. in 1867.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Brazil and Cuba abolished slavery in the 1880s, with Cuba ending it in 1886 and Brazil in 1888.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] While actors like Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda in Cuba and Adelina Charuteira in Brazil worked to end slavery, it was enslaved people themselves who worked daily to chip away at enslavers' local authority.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] These practices are regionally specific based on the legal customs of the region that enslaved people knew well from centuries of interactions with Iberian slave laws.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] A key avenue for these legal arguments was the prominence of "lo extrajudicial", a field of legal interactions adjacent to a lawsuit explained by historian Bianca Premo as consisting of out-of-court settlements, public revelations, and face-to-face encounters.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The suffering of women in slavery was a common trope consistently used in abolitionists' rhetoric on both sides of the Atlantic.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] This was especially true as it relates to the image of suffering mothers and their children.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Towards the end of the nineteenth century as slavery was coming to an end throughout the Atlantic world, images appearing in abolitionist publications routinely included images of families being torn apart and pregnant women being forced to do hard labor.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] As countries imposed "free womb laws" to soften the image of slavery and bring about gradual emancipation, for many it raised the question of the justice of women being used to carry out emancipation without benefiting from it themselves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Speeches given on the topic at the time focused on mothers and compared them to "all other mothers", using motherhood to level the subjects and objects of their speech.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Women were also often on the forefront of the abolition movement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Authors such as Harriet Beecher Stowe (United States) and Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda (Brazil) used their novels to call into question the humanity of slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Women such as the Grimké Sisters, Abigail Adams, Elizabeth Cady Stanton and others used their connections to political movements to advocate for the abolition of slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women such as Phillis Wheatley and Harriet Tubman took matters into their own hands by challenging the institution of slavery through their writing and their actions.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Enslaved women like Adelina Charuteira used their mobility as street vendors and as much access as they had to literacy to spread information about abolition between freedom-seeking people and local abolitionist networks.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] White and black opponents of slavery, who played a considerable role in the movement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] This list includes some escaped slaves, who were traditionally called abolitionists.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The first international attempt to address the abolition of slavery was the World Anti-Slavery Convention, organised by the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society at Exeter Hall in London, on 12–23 June 1840.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] This was however an attempt made by NGOs, not by state and governments.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In the late 19th century, the issue was addressed on an international level by states and governments.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The Brussels Anti-Slavery Conference 1889–90 addressed slavery on a semi-global level via the representatives of the colonial powers.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] It had concluded with the Brussels Conference Act of 1890.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The 1890 Act was revised by the Convention of Saint-Germain-en-Laye 1919.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] During the 20th century the issue of slavery was addressed by the League of Nations, which founded commissions to investigate and eradicate the institution of slavery and slave trade worldwide.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The Temporary Slavery Commission (TSC), which was founded in 1924, conducted a global investigation and filed a report, and a convention was drawn up to hasten the total abolition of slavery and the slave trade.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The 1926 Slavery Convention, which was founded upon the investigation of the TSC of the League of Nations, was a turning point in banning global slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In 1932, the League formed the Committee of Experts on Slavery (CES) to review the result and enforcement of the 1926 Slavery Convention, which resulted in a new international investigation under the first permanent slavery committee, the Advisory Committee of Experts on Slavery (ACE).
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The ACE conducted a major international investigation on slavery and slave trade, inspecting all the colonial empires and the territories under their control between 1934 and 1939.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted in 1948 by the UN General Assembly, explicitly banned slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] After World War II, chattel slavery was formally abolished by law in almost the entire world, with the exception of the Arabian Peninsula and some parts of Africa.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Chattel slavery was still legal in Saudi Arabia, in Yemen, in the Trucial States and in Oman, and slaves were supplied to the Arabian Peninsula via the Red Sea slave trade.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The United Nations 1956 Supplementary Convention on the Abolition of Slavery was convened to outlaw and ban slavery worldwide, including child slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In November 1962, Faisal of Saudi Arabia finally prohibited the owning of slaves in Saudi Arabia, followed by the abolition of slavery in Yemen in 1962, slavery in Dubai 1963 and slavery in Oman in 1970.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In December 1966, the UN General Assembly adopted the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which was developed from the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Article 4 of this international treaty bans slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The treaty came into force in March 1976 after it had been ratified by 35 nations.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] As of November 2003, 104 nations had ratified the treaty.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] However, illegal forced labor involves millions of people in the 21st century, 43% for sexual exploitation and 32% for economic exploitation.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Currently, the Anti-trafficking Coordination Team Initiative (ACT Team Initiative), a coordinated effort between the U.S.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Departments of Justice, Homeland Security, and Labor, addresses human trafficking.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] The International Labour Organization estimates that there are 20.9 million victims of human trafficking globally, including 5.5 million children, of which 55% are women and girls.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] In societies with large proportions of the population working in conditions of slavery or serfdom, stroke-of-the-pen laws declaring abolition can have thorough-going social, economic and political consequences.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p01] Issues of compensation/redemption, land-redistribution and citizenship can prove intractable.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] People in modern times have commemorated abolitionist movements and the abolition of slavery in different ways around the world.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] The United Nations General Assembly declared 2004 the International Year to Commemorate the Struggle against Slavery and its Abolition.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] This proclamation marked the bicentenary of the proclamation of the first modern slavery-free state, Haiti.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Numerous exhibitions, events and research programmes became associated with the initiative.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] 2007 witnessed major exhibitions in British museums and galleries to mark the anniversary of the 1807 abolition act – 1807 Commemorated 2008 marked the 201st anniversary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade in the British Empire.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] It also marked the 175th anniversary of the abolition of slavery in the British Empire.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] The Faculty of Law at the University of Ottawa held a major international conference entitled, "Routes to Freedom: Reflections on the Bicentenary of the Abolition of the Slave Trade", from 14 to 16 March 2008.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Abolitionist constitutionalism is a line of thinking which invokes the historical view of the Constitution of the United States as an abolitionist document.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] It calls for an appeal to constitutionalism and progressive constitutionalism.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] This vision is interdisciplinary and finds its roots in the anti-slavery movement in the United States of America and is largely based on the tenet that current state institutions, particularly the carceral system, is rooted in the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Some constitutional abolitionists critique the claim that the Constitution was pro-slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionist constitutionalism calls for the idea of dignity and the use of jurisprudence to address social inequalities.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Constitution was pro-slavery, the Reconstruction Amendments can be seen as a compromise for freedom, without allowing for the full abolition.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Criminal punishment was a major way that Southern states maintained the exploitation of black labor and effectively nullified the Reconstruction Amendments.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] This was done namely through Black Codes, harsh vagrancy laws, apprenticeship laws and extreme punishment for black people.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] The Reconstruction Amendments in their aim to promote citizenship and emancipation are believed by these thinkers to still be guiding principles in the fight for freedom and abolition.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] There are suggestions that a broad reading of the Thirteenth Amendment can convey an abolitionist vision of the freedom advocated for by black people in the public sphere beyond emancipation.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Section one of the Fourteenth Amendment was used by many abolitionist lawyers and activists throughout the North to advance the case against slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Proponents of abolitionist constitutionalism believe the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Amendments can be used today to extend the abolitionist logics to the various current barriers to injustices that are faced by marginalized peoples.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Just like abolitionism more generally, abolitionist constitutionalism seeks to provide a vision which will lead to the abolition of many different neoliberal state institutions, such as the prison industrial complex, the wage system, and policing.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] This is tied to a belief that white supremacy is woven into the fabric of legal state institutions.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Radical abolitionists are often marginalized.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] There is a belief that constitutionalism as a main tenet of radical abolitionism can change and appeal to the popular opinion more.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Historically, slavery abolitionists have had to use the public meaning of Constitutional terms in order in their fight against slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Constitutional abolitionists are generally in favour of incremental changes that follow the principles of the Reconstructive Amendments.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Some argue that the narrative and scholarly literature around Reconstruction Amendments is not coherent regarding their original aims.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] On 10 December 1948, the General Assembly of the United Nations adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Although outlawed in most countries, slavery is nonetheless practised secretly in many parts of the world.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Enslavement still takes place in the United States, Europe, and Latin America, as well as parts of Africa, the Middle East, and South Asia.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Modern slavery keeps around 50 million people from exercising their freedom.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] In Mauritania alone, estimates are that up to 600,000 men, women and children, or 20% of the population, are enslaved.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Modern-day abolitionists have emerged over the last several years, as awareness of slavery around the world has grown, with groups such as Anti-Slavery International, the American Anti-Slavery Group, International Justice Mission, and Free the Slaves working to rid the world of slavery.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] In the United States, The Action Group to End Human Trafficking and Modern-Day Slavery is a coalition of NGOs, foundations and corporations working to develop a policy agenda for abolishing slavery and human trafficking.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Since 1997, the United States Department of Justice has, through work with the Coalition of Immokalee Workers, prosecuted six individuals in Florida on charges of slavery in the agricultural industry.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] These prosecutions have led to freedom for over 1000 enslaved workers in the tomato and orange fields of South Florida.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] This is only one example of the contemporary fight against slavery worldwide.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Slavery exists most widely in agricultural labor, apparel and sex industries, and service jobs in some regions.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] In 2000, the United States passed the Victims of Trafficking and Violence Protection Act (TVPA) "to combat trafficking in persons, especially into the sex trade, slavery, and involuntary servitude".
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] The 13th amendment abolished slavery in the United States "except as a punishment for crime whereof the party shall have been duly convicted".
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] In 2018, Colorado became the first state to remove similar language in its state constitution by a legislatively referred ballot referendum.
[src:animal-liberation-front/abolitionism-p02] Other states have followed suit, but implementation has relied on court rulings.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The **Animal Liberation Front** (**ALF**) is an anarchist international, leaderless, decentralized movement that emerged in Britain in the 1970s, evolving from the Bands of Mercy.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] It operates without a formal leadership structure and engages in direct actions aimed at opposing animal cruelty and exploitation.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] These actions include removing animals from laboratories and farms, damaging facilities, providing veterinary care, and establishing sanctuaries for those animals.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Participants describe their efforts as non-violent and compare their activities to a modern-day Underground Railroad.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] However, the ALF has also been criticized and labeled as an eco-terrorist organization by some groups and individuals.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Active in over 40 countries, the ALF operates through clandestine cells, often consisting of small groups or individuals.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] This decentralized and covert structure makes it challenging for authorities to monitor or infiltrate the organization.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] According to Robin Webb of the Animal Liberation Press Office, this structure is a key reason for the ALF's resistance, stating "That is why the ALF cannot be smashed; it cannot be effectively infiltrated, it cannot be stopped.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Activists associated with the ALF describe the movement as non-violent.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] According to the ALF's guidelines, actions that promote animal liberation and take all reasonable precautions to avoid harm to both human and nonhuman life can be attributed to the ALF, including acts of vandalism that may cause economic damage.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] There has nevertheless been widespread criticism for its alleged involvement in acts of violence and for the failure of some spokespersons and activists to condemn such actions.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] This criticism has led to dissent within the animal rights movement regarding the use of violence and has attracted increased attention from law enforcement and intelligence agencies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In 2005, the ALF was listed in a United States Department of Homeland Security planning document as a domestic terrorist threat, prompting the allocation of resources to monitor the group.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] That same year, FBI deputy assistant director John Lewis described "ecoterrorism" and the "animal rights movement" as the number one domestic terrorism threat.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In the United Kingdom, ALF activities are classified as examples of domestic extremism and were monitored by the National Extremism Tactical Coordination Unit, which was established in 2004 to oversee illegal animal rights activity.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The origins of the ALF can be traced back to December 1963 when British journalist John Prestige attended a Devon and Somerset Staghounds event.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] During the event, Prestige witnessed the hunting and killing of a pregnant deer, an experience that prompted him to form the Hunt Saboteurs Association (HSA) in protest.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The HSA initially consisted of volunteers who were trained to disrupt hunts by blowing horns and laying false scents to mislead the hounds.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] According to animal rights writer Noel Molland, one of the groups within the HSA was established in 1971 by Ronnie Lee, a law student from Luton.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In 1972, Lee, along with fellow activist Cliff Goodman, concluded that more militant tactics were necessary to further their cause.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] They decided to revive the name of a 19th-century RSPCA youth group, The Bands of Mercy, and formed a small group of about half a dozen activists known as the Band of Mercy.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] This group began targeting hunters' vehicles by slashing tires and breaking windows, aiming to prevent hunts from starting rather than disrupting them once underway.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In 1973, the Band of Mercy became aware that Hoechst Pharmaceuticals was constructing a research laboratory in Milton Keynes.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] On 10 November 1973, two members of the group set fire to the building, resulting in £26,000 worth of damage.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The activists returned six days later to ignite the remains of the structure.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] This incident marked the first known act of arson within the animal liberation movement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In June 1974, two members of the Band set fire to boats involved in the annual seal cull off the coast of Norfolk; according to Molland, this incident contributed to the cessation of the cull.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Between June and August 1974, the Band carried out eight raids targeting animal-testing laboratories, as well as other actions against chicken breeders and gun shops, causing damage to buildings and vehicles.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The group's first recorded act of "animal liberation" occurred during this period when activists removed half a dozen guinea pigs from a guinea pig farm in Wiltshire, leading the owner to close the business out of concern for further incidents.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The use of property damage as a tactic created a rift within the emerging animal rights movement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In July 1974, the Hunt Saboteurs Association publicly distanced itself from the Band of Mercy, offering a £250 reward for information leading to the identification of its members.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The Association stated, "We approve of their ideals but are opposed to their methods," signaling disapproval of the Band's approach.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In August 1974, Ronnie Lee and Cliff Goodman were arrested for their involvement in a raid on the Oxford Laboratory Animal Colonies in Bicester, a case that earned them the moniker "Bicester Two".
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] During their trial, daily demonstrations took place outside the court, with supporters including Lee's local Labour MP, Ivor Clemitson.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Both Lee and Goodman were sentenced to three years in prison.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] While incarcerated, Lee initiated the movement's first hunger strike to secure access to vegan food and clothing.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] After serving 12 months, Lee was released on parole in the spring of 1976, emerging more militant than ever.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] He regrouped with the remaining Band of Mercy activists and recruited around two dozen new members, forming a group of approximately 30 individuals.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] According to Molland, Lee felt that the name "Band of Mercy" no longer accurately reflected what he envisioned as a revolutionary movement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Seeking a name that would instill fear in those who exploited animals, Lee founded the Animal Liberation Front.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The methods used by the ALF and the ideology it develops are thus part of the broader trajectory of the anarchist movement between the later half of the 20th and the first half of the 21st century.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Like other anarchists, they are also criminalized as terrorists, in their case as eco-terrorists.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The Animal Liberation Front operates with both underground and above-ground components and is entirely decentralized with no formal hierarchy.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] This decentralized nature helps limit legal responsibility.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Several above-ground organizations support the movement's covert activities.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The Animal Liberation Front Supporters Group (ALF SG) provides support to activists in prison, who are recognized as prisoners of conscience, and allows membership through a monthly fee.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The Vegan Prisoners Support Group, established in 1994, works with UK prison authorities to ensure that ALD prisoners have access to vegan supplies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The Animal Liberation Press Office collects and disseminates anonymous communiqués from volunteers; it operates as an ostensibly independent group funded by public donations, though the High Court in London ruled in 2006 that its press officer in the UK, Robin Webb, was a pivotal figure in the ALF.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] There are three publications associated with the ALF.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] *Arkangel* was a British bi-annual magazine founded by Ronnie Lee.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] *Bite Back* is a website where activists leave claims of responsibility; it published a "Direct Action Report" in 2005 stating that, in 2004 alone, ALF activists had removed 17,262 animals from facilities and had claimed 554 acts of vandalism and arson.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] *No Compromise* is a US-based website that also reports on ALF actions.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] ALF activists argue that animals should not be viewed as property and that scientists and industry have no right to assume ownership of living beings who are the "subjects-of-a-life," in the words of philosopher Tom Regan.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In the view of the ALF, failing to recognize this is an example of speciesism—the ascription of different values to beings on the basis of their species membership alone, which they argue is as ethically flawed as racism or sexism.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] They reject the animal welfare position that more humane treatment is needed for animals; they say their aim is empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Activists argue that the animals they remove from laboratories or farms are "liberated", not "stolen", because they were never rightfully owned in the first place.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Although the ALF members reject violence against people, many activists support property crime, comparing the destruction of animal laboratories and other facilities to resistance fighters blowing up gas chambers in Nazi Germany.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] An ALF activist involved in an arson attack on the University of Arizona told *No Compromise* in 1996: "[I]t is much the same thing as the abolitionists who fought against slavery going in and burning down the quarters or tearing down the auction block ...
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The provision against violence in the ALF code has triggered divisions within the movement and allegations of hypocrisy from the ALF's critics.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] It was named as a terrorist threat by the U.S.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Department of Homeland Security in January 2005.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In March 2005, a speech from the Counterterrorism Division of the FBI stated that: "The eco-terrorist movement has given rise and notoriety to groups such as the Animal Liberation Front, or ALF, and the Earth Liberation Front (ELF).
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Best and trauma surgeon Jerry Vlasak, both of whom have volunteered for the North American press office, were banned from entering the UK in 2004 and 2005 after making statements that appeared to support violence against people.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Vlasak told an animal rights conferences in 2003: "I don't think you'd have to kill—assassinate—too many vivisectors before you would see a marked decrease in the amount of vivisection going on.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] And I think for five lives, 10 lives, 15 human lives, we could save a million, two million, 10 million non-human animals." Best coined the term "extensional self-defence" to describe actions carried out in defense of animals by human beings acting as proxies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] He argues that activists have the moral right to engage in acts of sabotage or even violence because animals are unable to fight back themselves.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Best argues that the principle of extensional self-defense mirrors the penal code statues known as the necessity defense, which can be invoked when a defendant believes the illegal act was necessary to avoid imminent and great harm.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The nature of the ALF as a leaderless resistance means support for Vlasak and Best is hard to measure.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] An anonymous volunteer interviewed in 2005 for CBS's *60 Minutes* said of Vlasak: "[H]e doesn't operate with our endorsement or our support or our appreciation, the support of the ALF.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] We have a strict code of non-violence ...
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Philosopher Peter Singer of Princeton University has argued that ALF direct action can only be regarded as a just cause if it is non-violent, and that the ALF is at its most effective when uncovering evidence of animal abuse that other tactics could not expose.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] He cites 1984's "Unnecessary Fuss" campaign, when ALF raided the University of Pennsylvania's head-injury research clinic and removed footage showing researchers laughing at the brain damage of conscious baboons, as an example.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The university responded that the treatment of the animals conformed to National Institutes of Health (NIH) guidelines, but as a result of the publicity, the lab was closed down, the chief veterinarian fired, and the university placed on probation.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Barbara Orlans, a former animal researcher with the NIH, now with the Kennedy Institute of Ethics, writes that the case stunned the biomedical community, and is today considered one of the most significant cases in the ethics of using animals in research.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Singer argues that if the ALF would focus on this kind of direct action, instead of sabotage, it would appeal to the minds of reasonable people.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Against this, Steven Best writes that industries and governments have too much institutional and financial bias for reason to prevail.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Peter Hughes of the University of Sunderland cites a 1988 raid in the UK led by ALF activist Barry Horne as an example of positive ALF direct action.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Horne and four other activists decided to free Rocky, a dolphin who had lived in a small concrete pool in Marineland in Morecambe for 20 years, by moving him 180 metres (590 ft) from his pool to the sea.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The police spotted them carrying a homemade dolphin stretcher, and they were convicted of conspiracy to steal, but they continued to campaign for Rocky's release.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Marineland eventually agreed to sell him for £120,000, money that was raised with the help of the Born Free Foundation and the Mail on Sunday, and in 1991 Rocky was transferred to an 80-acre (320,000 m2) lagoon reserve in the Turks and Caicos Islands, then released.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Hughes writes that the ALF action helped to create a paradigm shift in the UK toward seeing dolphins as "individual actors", as a result of which, he writes, there are now no captive dolphins in the UK.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Rachel Monaghan of the University of Ulster writes that, in their first year of operation alone, ALF actions accounted for £250,000 worth of damage, targeting butcher shops, furriers, circuses, slaughterhouses, breeders, and fast-food restaurants.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] She writes that the ALF philosophy was that violence can only take place against sentient life forms, and therefore focusing on property destruction and the removal of animals from laboratories and farms was consistent with a philosophy of non-violence, despite the damage they were causing.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In 1974, Ronnie Lee insisted that direct action be "limited only by reverence of life and hatred of violence", and in 1979, he wrote that many ALF raids had been called off because of the risk to life.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Kim Stallwood, a national organiser for the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection (BUAV) in the 1980s, writes that the public's response to early ALF raids that removed animals was very positive, in large measure because of the non-violence policy.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] When Mike Huskisson removed three beagles from a tobacco study at ICI in June 1975, the media portrayed him as a hero.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Robin Webb writes that ALF volunteers were viewed as the "Robin Hoods of the animal welfare world".
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Stallwood writes that they saw ALF activism as part of their opposition to the state, rather than as an end-in-itself, and did not want to adhere to non-violence.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In the early 1980s, the BUAV, an anti-vivisection group founded by Frances Power Cobbe in 1898, was among the ALF's supporters.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Stallwood writes that it donated part of its office space rent-free to the ALF Supporters Group, and gave ALF actions uncritical support in its newspaper, *The Liberator*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In 1982, a group of ALF activists, including Roger Yates, now a sociologist at University College, Dublin, and Dave McColl, a director of Sea Shepherd Conservation Society, became members of the BUAV's executive committee, and used their position to radicalize the organization.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Stallwood writes that the new executive believed all political action to be a waste of time and wanted the BUAV to devote its resources exclusively to direct action.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] He writes: "Where was the intelligent debate about tactics and strategies that went beyond the mindless rhetoric and emotional elitism pervading much of the self-produced direct action literature?
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In short, what had happened to the animals' interests?" In 1984, the BUAV board reluctantly voted to expel the ALF SG from its premises and withdraw its political support, after which, Stallwood writes, the ALF became increasingly isolated.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] There are conflicting accounts of when the ALF first emerged in the United States.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The FBI writes that animal rights activists had a history of committing low-level criminal activity in the U.S. dating back to the 1970s.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Freeman Wicklund and Kim Stallwood say that the first ALF action in the U.S. was on 29 May 1977, when researchers Ken LeVasseur and Steve Sipman released two dolphins, Puka and Kea, into the ocean from the University of Hawaii's Marine Mammal Laboratory.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Kathy Snow Guillermo writes in *Monkey Business* that the first U.S.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] ALF action was the removal, on 22 September 1981, of the Silver Spring monkeys, 17 lab monkeys in the legal custody of People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA), after a researcher who had been experimenting on them was arrested for alleged violations of cruelty legislation.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] When the court ruled that the monkeys be returned to the researcher, they mysteriously disappeared, only to reappear five days later when PETA learned that legal action against the researcher could not proceed without the monkeys as evidence.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Ingrid Newkirk, the president of PETA, writes that the first ALF cell was set up in late 1982, after a police officer she calls "Valerie" responded to the publicity triggered by the Silver Spring monkeys case, and flew to England to be trained by the ALF.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Posing as a reporter, Valerie was put in touch with Ronnie Lee by Kim Stallwood, who at the time was working for the BUAV.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Lee directed her to a training camp, where she was taught how to break into laboratories.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Newkirk writes that Valerie returned to Maryland and set up an ALF cell, with the first raid taking place on 24 December 1982 against Howard University, where 24 cats were removed, some of whose back legs had been crippled.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Jo Shoesmith, an American attorney and animal rights activist, says Newkirk's account of "Valerie" is not only fictionalized, as Newkirk acknowledges, but totally fictitious.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Two early ALF raids led to the closure of several university studies.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] A 28 May 1984 raid on the University of Pennsylvania's head injury clinic caused $60,000 worth of damage and saw the removal of 60 hours of tapes, which showed the researchers laughing as they used a hydraulic device to cause brain damage to baboons.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The tapes were turned over to PETA, who produced a 26-minute video called *Unnecessary Fuss*.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The head injury clinic was closed, the university's chief veterinarian was fired, and the university was put on probation.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] On 20 April 1985, acting on a tip-off from a student, the ALF raided a laboratory in the University of California, Riverside, causing $700,000 in damages and removing 468 animals.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] These included Britches, a five-week-old macaque, who had been separated from his mother at birth and left alone with his eyes sewn shut and a sonar device on his head as part of a study into blindness.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The raid, which was taped by the ALF, caused eight of the laboratory's seventeen active research projects to be shut down, and the university said years of medical research were lost.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The raid prompted National Institutes of Health director James Wyngaarden to argue that the raids should be regarded as acts of terrorism.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Monaghan writes that, around 1982, there was a noticeable shift in the non-violent position, and not one approved by everyone in the movement.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Some activists began to make personal threats against individuals, followed by letter bombs and threats to contaminate food, the latter representing yet another shift to threatening the general public, rather than specific targets.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In 1982, letter bombs were sent to all four major party leaders in the UK, including Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The first major food scare happened in November 1984, with the ALF claiming to the media that it had contaminated Mars Bars as part of a campaign to force the Mars company to stop conducting tooth decay tests on monkeys.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] On 17 November, the *Sunday Mirror* received a call from the ALF saying it had injected Mars Bars in stores throughout the country with rat poison.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The call was followed by a letter containing a Mars Bar, presumed to be contaminated, and the claim that these were on sale in London, Leeds, York, Southampton, and Coventry.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Millions of bars were removed from shelves and Mars halted production, at a cost to the company of $4.5 million.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The ALF admitted the claims had been a hoax.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Similar contamination claims were later made against L'Oréal and Lucozade.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The letter bombs were claimed by the Animal Rights Militia (ARM), although the initial statement in November 1984 by David Mellor, then a Home Office minister, stated that it was the Animal Liberation Front who had claimed responsibility.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Ronnie Lee, who had earlier insisted on the importance of the ALF's non-violence policy, seemed to support the idea.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] An article signed by RL—presumed to be Ronnie Lee—in the October 1984 ALF Supporters Group newsletter, suggested that activists set up "fresh groups ... under new names whose policies do not preclude the use of violence toward animal abusers".
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] No activist is known to have conducted operations under both the ALF and ARM banners, but overlap is assumed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Terrorism expert Paul Wilkinson has written that the ALF, the Justice Department, and the ARM are essentially the same thing, and Robert Garner of the University of Leicester writes that it would be pointless to argue otherwise, given the nature of the movement as a leaderless resistance.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] From 1983 onwards, a series of fire bombs exploded in department stores that sold fur, with the intention of triggering the sprinkler systems in order to cause damage, although several stores were partly or completely destroyed.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In September 1985, incendiary devices were placed under the cars of Sharat Gangoli and Stuart Walker, both animal researchers with the British Industrial Biological Research Association (BIBRA), wrecking both vehicles but with no injuries, and the ARM claimed responsibility.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In January 1986, the ARM said it had placed devices under the cars of four employees of Huntingdon Life Sciences, timed to explode an hour apart from each other.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] A further device was placed under the car of Andor Sebesteny, a researcher for the Imperial Cancer Research Fund, which he spotted before it exploded.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The next major attacks on individual researchers took place in 1990, when the cars of two veterinary researchers were destroyed by sophisticated explosive devices in two separate explosions.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In February 1989, an explosion damaged the Senate House bar in Bristol University, an attack claimed by the unknown "Animal Abused Society".
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In June 1990, two days apart, bombs exploded in the cars of Margaret Baskerville, a veterinary surgeon working at Porton Down, a chemical research defence establishment, and Patrick Max Headley, a physiologist at Bristol University.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Baskerville escaped without injury by jumping through the window of her mini-jeep when a bomb using a mercury-tilt device exploded next to the fuel tank.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] During the attack on Headley—which *New Scientist* writes involved the use of plastic explosives—a 13-month-old baby in a push-chair suffered flash burns, shrapnel wounds, and a partially severed finger.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] A wave of letter bombs followed in 1993, one of which was opened by the head of the Hereford site of GlaxoSmithKline, causing burns to his hands and face.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Eleven similar devices were intercepted in postal sorting offices.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The nature of the ALF exposes its name to the risk of being used by activists who reject its non-violence platform, or by opponents conducting so-called "false-flag" operations, designed to make the ALF appear violent.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] That same uncertainty provides genuine ALF activists with plausible deniability should an operation go wrong, by denying that the act was "authentically ALF".
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Several of the incidents in 1989 and 1990 were described by the movement as false flag operations.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] No known entity claimed responsibility for the attacks, which were condemned within the animal rights movement and by ALF activists.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Keith Mann writes that it did not seem plausible that activists known for making simple incendiary devices from household components would suddenly switch to mercury-tilt switches and plastic explosives, then never be heard from again.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] A few days after the bombings, the unknown "British Animal Rights Society" claimed responsibility for attaching a nail bomb to a Huntsman's Land Rover in Somerset.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Forensic evidence led police to arrest the owner of the vehicle, who admitted he had bombed his own car to discredit the animal rights movement and asked for two similar offences to be taken into consideration.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The Baskerville and Headley bombers were never apprehended.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In 2018 the London Metropolitan Police apologised for the activities of one of their undercover agents who had infiltrated the group.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] A police officer using the name "Christine Green" had been involved in the illegal release of a large number of mink from a farm in Ringwood in 1998.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The mission had been approved by senior officers in the police.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Property destruction began to increase substantially after several high-profile campaigns closed down facilities perceived to be abusive to animals.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Consort Kennels, a facility breeding beagles for animal testing; Hillgrove Farm, which bred cats; and Newchurch Farm, which bred guinea pigs, were all closed after being targeted by animal rights campaigns that appeared to involve the ALF.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In the UK, the financial year 1991–1992 saw around 100 refrigerated meat trucks destroyed by incendiary devices at a cost of around £5 million.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Butchers' locks were superglued, shrink-wrapped meats were pierced in supermarkets, slaughterhouses and refrigerated meat trucks were set on fire.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In 1999, ALF activists became involved in the international Stop Huntingdon Animal Cruelty (SHAC) campaign to close Huntingdon Life Sciences (HLS), Europe's largest animal-testing laboratory.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The Southern Poverty Law Center, which monitors U.S. domestic extremism, has described SHAC's *modus operandi* as "frankly terroristic tactics similar to those of anti-abortion extremists".
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] ALF activist Donald Currie was jailed for 12 years and placed on probation for life in December 2006 after being found guilty of planting homemade bombs on the doorsteps of businessmen with links to HLS.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] HLS director Brian Cass was attacked by men wielding pick-axe handles in February 2001.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] David Blenkinsop was one of those convicted of the attack, someone who in the past had conducted actions in the name of the ALF.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Also in 1999, a freelance reporter, Graham Hall, said he had been attacked after producing a documentary critical of the ALF, which was aired on Channel 4.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The documentary showed ALF press officer Robin Webb appearing to give Hall—who was filming undercover while purporting to be an activist—advice about how to make an improvised explosive device, though Webb said his comments had been used out of context.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Hall said that, as a result of the documentary, he was abducted, tied to a chair, and had the letters "ALF" branded on his back, before being released 12 hours later with a warning not to tell the police.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] In June 2006, members of the ALF claimed responsibility for a firebomb attack on UCLA researcher Lynn Fairbanks, after a firebomb was placed on the doorstep of a house occupied by her 70-year-old tenant; according to the FBI, it was powerful enough to have killed the occupants, but failed to ignite.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The attack was credited by the acting chancellor of UCLA as helping to shape the Animal Enterprise Terrorism Act.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] On 20 January 2006, as part of *Operation Backfire*, the U.S.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] Department of Justice announced charges against nine Americans and two Canadian activists calling themselves the "family".
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] At least 9 of the 11 pleaded guilty to conspiracy and arson for their parts in a string of 20 arsons from 1996 through 2001, damage totalled $40 million.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The Department of Justice called the acts examples of domestic terrorism.
[src:animal-liberation-front/animal-liberation-front] The incidents included arson attacks against meat-processing plants, lumber companies, a high-tension power line, and a ski centre, in Oregon, Wyoming, Washington, California and Colorado between 1996 and 2001.
